A buffer that displays as

abc
def
ghi

with the cursor on the "e"
looks like this:


                  +-----------------------------+
                  | +-------------------------+ |
                  | |                         | |
                  | v                         | |
            	+-------------------+         | |
                |abc            L_NL|         | |
            	+-------------------+         | |
                  ^ |                         | |
                  | v                         | |
            	+-------------------+         | |
curwp->dotp---->|def            L_NL|         | |
            	+-------------------+         | |
curwp->doto=1     ^ |                         | |
                  | v                         | |
            	+-------------------+         | |
                |ghi            L_NL|         | |
            	+-------------------+         | |
                  ^ |                         | |
                  | v                         | |
            	+-------------------+         | |
curbp->linep--->|*EOB*              |         | |
            	+-------------------+         | |
                  ^ |                         | |
                  | +-------------------------+ |
                  +-----------------------------+

curbp->dotp is not meaningful when the buffer is displayed


================================================================

version 1.73: rewrote the "writeout" function to use only system calls, not
the standard library.  Seems significantly faster -- 66000 "line" iso file
(250MB) is read almost instantaneously, change a character, write it back. 
Three runs:

me 1.72:
real    0m4.728s    0m3.165s    0m3.719s
user    0m0.788s    0m0.816s    0m0.792s
sys     0m0.160s    0m0.128s    0m0.168s


me 1.73:
real    0m2.909s    0m2.914s    0m2.547s
user    0m0.096s    0m0.092s    0m0.124s
sys     0m0.176s    0m0.144s    0m0.168s

================================================================
Todo: a "update" command that updates a file in place (keeping the same 
inode) rather than creating a new inode.  

the basic file handling model currently is that all editing operations take
place on buffers; buffers are filled by the "readin" function, which opens a
file, reads it in to the buffer, then closes the file.  whenever a file is 
opened, its status is checked, and preserved in an array of struct stat 
named "file_data".  The key is the inode number (should also use filesystem 
id somehow).  When a file is written, if the write will overwrite an old 
file, the permissions of the old file should be matched.

the file handling needs to be rewritten from scratch -- the old design was 
designed to implement an abstraction over many different platforms -- unix, 
dos, windows, vms, etc -- but currently I only worry about the unix 
interface, and the abstraction layer gets in the way.  in particular, 
"fileio.c" should be folded into "file.c", and then the whole thing gone 
over in detail a couple of times.  all should be done in terms of open, 
close, read, write, instead of fopen etc.  ie, if possible, get rid of io 
library.  (done)

Need a better autosave/recovery mechanism -- perhaps the ",," files should 
have a tiny structure attached at the front, and the program should view 
these as potentially recoverable on start up -- ask "do you want to 
recover...". 
